		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Nous</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the philosophy journal, see <a href="/wiki/No%C3%BBs" title="Noûs">Noûs</a>.</div>
<p><b>Nous</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈnuːs/</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">Greek</a>: <span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">νοῦς</span> or <span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">νόος</span>) is a philosophical term for <a href="/wiki/Mind" title="Mind">mind</a> or <a href="/wiki/Intellect" title="Intellect" class="mw-redirect">intellect</a>. Outside of a philosophical context, it is used, in English, to denote "<a href="/wiki/Common_sense" title="Common sense">common sense</a>," with a different pronunciation (<span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/naʊs/</span>).</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
